After looking at your HeritrixLauncher class, I suspect the
problem is a thread deadlock.

requestCrawlStop() is only called inside doCrawlLoop, which
holds the synchronization monitor on the HeritrixLauncher
instance. However, one of the effects of requestCrawlStop()
is to inform all listeners that the crawl is ending -- and
this will usually happen from the ToeThread that notices
the crawl is truly ending, not the thread that initiated
the requestCrawlStop().

However, your SimpleCrawlStatusListener.crawlEnded() method
to receive this notification also seeks to obtain a lock
on the HeritrixLauncher instance -- resulting in a deadlock.

If this is the problem, it should be obvious in the SIGQUIT
thread dump -- that dump will itself run a simple deadlock
detection algorithm and show the results at the bottom of
the dump.

- Gordon @ IA

